{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 20:53:38.104569", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnostic report — multi‑tier Clos (fat‑tree) EBGP fabric\\n\\nScope and goal\\n- Assess overall network health, detect anomalies, localize any faulty devices, and identify root causes where present.\\n- Data used: host reachability sweep (pings) and FRR state (BGP summaries, BGP tables, routing tables) collected from leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, and super_spine_router_0.\\n\\nExecutive summary / high-level finding\\n- No critical anomalies detected. All tested hosts (PCs) are reachable (0% packet loss in the provided reachability tests). BGP sessions across the fabric are established and exchanging expected route counts. Control plane (BGP) appears converged and data plane (IP reachability) is functioning end‑to‑end for the exercised prefixes.\\n- No routers show BGP session Down/Idle/Active states in the provided outputs — all neighbors reported are in an Established state and are advertising/receiving prefixes as expected.\\n- Routing tables contain the expected /24 host networks and inter-router /31 links are present as connected routes.\\n\\nEvidence and key observations\\n\\n1) Host connectivity (data plane)\\n- get_reachability: multiple ping pairs (examples: pc_0_0 → pc_0_1 and pc_0_0 → pc_3_1) all show tx=rx, loss_percent=0.0 with small RTTs. Summary: data plane forwarding is working for the tested hosts.\\n\\n2) BGP control plane (per‑router summaries)\\n- leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200)\\n  - BGP router-id 172.16.1.1, neighbors = 8\\n  - Neighbor 172.16.1.0 (AS 65100) Up ~00:02:54, PfxRcd = 31 (receiving ~31 prefixes)\\n  - Other spine/super neighbors present; no sessions shown as down.\\n- leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201)\\n  - BGP router-id 172.16.1.3, neighbors = 8\\n  - Neighbor 172.16.1.2 (AS 65100) Up ~00:02:54, PfxRcd = 31\\n  - All neighbors present and exchanging prefixes.\\n- spine_router_0_0 (AS 65100)\\n  - BGP router-id 172.16.0.1, peers = 12\\n  - Neighbors toward super-spine(s) and leaves are Up and showing expected small PfxRcd counts (examples: neighbors to leaf ASes show PfxRcd = 1 where expected).\\n- spine_router_0_1 (AS 65101)\\n  - BGP router-id 172.16.0.3, peers = 12\\n  - All peers Up and exchanging expected prefixes.\\n- super_spine_router_0 (AS 65000)\\n  - BGP router-id 172.16.0.0, peers = 32\\n  - Many spine neighbors present; all sessions established; PfxRcd values consistent with expected prefix advertisement counts.\\n\\n3) BGP RIB contents / route selection\\n- leaf_router_0_0: its local /24 (10.0.0.0/24) is shown as locally-originated (next-hop 0.0.0.0). Other 10.0.X.0/24 networks are present with multiple next‑hops (multipath / many candidate next-hops) and a single selected best route in each case (expected in a multi-path Clos).\\n- spine and super-spine tables show the full set of expected pod host /24s and show multiple equal / alternative paths where the topology provides them (consistent with Clos redundancy).\\n- show ip route outputs confirm connected /31 inter-router links and BGP learned /24 prefixes are installed in the RIB/FIB (seen as B/* entries and C for connected interfaces).\\n\\n4) Operational metrics / anomalies inspected\\n- BGP message counters: a minority of peers show higher MsgSent/MsgRcvd counts (e.g., some entries 96/72). This is not accompanied by session flaps or route instability in the collected snapshots — the sessions are established and prefix counts are stable. The higher message counts likely reflect timing differences during the data collection or more route updates seen by certain peers, not an ongoing session problem.\\n- No sessions are showing non‑Established or showing high OutQ/InQ values — there are no signs of BGP buffer/queue buildup in the outputs.\\n- No missing critical prefixes: all expected 10.0.X.0/24 networks are present in the BGP tables of multiple routers and in the forwarding tables.\\n\\nDevice localization (faulty devices)\\n- No device exhibits evidence of being faulty in the collected data:\\n  - All five FRR routers queried (leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, super_spine_router_0) have their BGP neighbors in Established state and are advertising/receiving expected prefix counts.\\n  - Routing tables on the routers show the connected inter-router /31 addresses and the expected /24 prefixes were installed.\\n  - Data plane reachability matches control plane state.\\n\\nRoot‑cause analysis\\n- Because the control plane and data plane are healthy and consistent in the provided outputs, there is no evidence of a root cause for failure. No BGP session failures, no missing routes, and no host reachability issues were found.\\n- Minor observation: some peers show different BGP table versions and unequal message counts; these are symptomatic of asynchronous timing between routers during the snapshot and not of a protocol failure. No persistent withdraws/flaps or session resets were observed in the captured outputs.\\n\\nDetailed supporting snippets (representative)\\n- leaf_router_0_0: neighbor 172.16.1.0 Up 00:02:54, PfxRcd = 31; 10.0.0.0/24 is locally originated.\\n- leaf_router_0_1: neighbor 172.16.1.2 Up 00:02:54, PfxRcd = 31; 10.0.1.0/24 locally originated.\\n- spine_router_0_0 / spine_router_0_1: peers to super-spine(s) and leaves Up; per-router PfxRcd counts consistent with expected topology.\\n- super_spine_router_0: peers = 32, all neighbors Up, receiving advertised prefixes from spines.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- Network health: GOOD. BGP converged across the fabric and IP reachability works for tested hosts. No faults or misconfigurations evident from the collected state.\\n- No faulty devices identified and no root cause for outage or degradation found.\\n\\nIf you want, next diagnostic steps I can run (only upon your request)\\n- Interface-level checks (ifconfig / ip addr) and ethtool on specific interfaces if you suspect link errors.\\n- BGP debug/logs or incremental monitoring for flaps if you observed intermittent issues outside these snapshots.\\n- More granular traffic tests (iperf) between specific hosts to verify throughput/latency under load.\\n\\n(Per your instruction, I have not proposed mitigations — report focuses on detection, localization, and root‑cause assessment.), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='3d7c7c83-f37e-42a2-a4f3-126bd362b14c'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
